# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:page/dollar-sign] The explicitly double-barred (Dollar sign with two vertical lines) sign is called *cifrão* in the Portuguese language.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The sign is also used in several compound currency symbols, such as the Brazilian real (R$) and the United States dollar (US$): in local use, the nationality prefix is usually omitted.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In countries that have other currency symbols, the US dollar is often assumed and the "US" prefix omitted.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The one- and two-stroke versions are often considered mere stylistic (typeface) variants, although in some places and epochs one of them may have been specifically assigned, by law or custom, to a specific currency.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The Unicode computer encoding standard defines a single code for both.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In most English-speaking countries that use that symbol, it is placed to the left of the amount specified, e.g.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The symbol appears in business correspondence in the 1770s from the West Indies referring to the Spanish American peso, also known as "Spanish dollar" or "piece of eight" in British America.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The Spanish coins provided the model for the currency that the United States adopted in 1792, and for the larger coins of the new Spanish American republics, such as the Mexican peso, Argentine peso, Peruvian real, and Bolivian sol coins.
[src:page/dollar-sign] With the Coinage Act of 1792, the United States Congress created the U.S. dollar, defining it to have "the value of a Spanish milled dollar as the same is now current" but a variety of foreign coins were deemed to be legal tender until the Coinage Act of 1857 ended this status.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The earliest U.S. dollar coins did not have any dollar symbol.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The first occurrence in print is claimed to be from 1790s, by a Philadelphia printer Archibald Binny, creator of the Monticello typeface.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The $1 United States Note issued by the United States in 1869 included a large symbol consisting of a 'U' with the right bar overlapping an 'S' like a single-bar dollar sign, as well as a very small double-stroke dollar sign in the legal warning against forgery *see picture*.
[src:page/dollar-sign] It is still uncertain, however, how the dollar sign came to represent the Spanish American peso.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The numerous currencies called "dollar" use the dollar sign to express money amounts.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The sign is also generally used for the many currencies called "peso" (except the Philippine peso, which uses the symbol "₱").
[src:page/dollar-sign] Within a country the dollar/peso sign may be used alone.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In other cases, and to avoid ambiguity in international usage, it is usually combined with other glyphs, e.g.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Particularly in professional contexts, the unambiguous ISO 4217 three letter code (AUD, MXN, USD, etc.) is preferred.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The exception is French-speaking Canada, where the dollar symbol usually appears after the number, the same as the spoken order, e.g., "5 $" for "*cinq dollars*".
[src:page/dollar-sign] In Portugal, Brazil, and other parts of the Portuguese Empire, the two-stroke variant of the sign named ***cifrão*** (Portuguese pronunciation: [siˈfɾɐ̃w] ⓘ; plural *cifrões*) has been used as the thousands separator in the national currency, the real (plural "réis", abbreviated "Rs.").
[src:page/dollar-sign] For instance, 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)500 would be equivalent to 123500 réis.
[src:page/dollar-sign] This usage is attested in 1775, but may be older by a century or more.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The cifrão is always written with two vertical lines like (Dollar sign with two vertical lines), and is the official sign of the Cape Verdean escudo (ISO 4217: CVE).
[src:page/dollar-sign] In 1911, Portugal redefined the national currency as the escudo, worth 1000 réis, and divided into 100 *centavos*; but the *cifrão* continued to be used as the decimal separator, so that 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 123.50 escudos or 123 escudos and 50 centavos.
[src:page/dollar-sign] This usage ended in 2002 when the country switched to the euro.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Cape Verde, a republic and former Portuguese colony, similarly switched from the real to their local escudo and centavos in 1914, and retains the *cifrão* usage as decimals separator as of 2021.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Brazil retained the real and the *cifrão* as thousands separator until 1942, when it switched to the Brazilian cruzeiro, with comma as the decimals separator.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The dollar sign, officially with one stroke but often rendered with two, was retained as part of the currency symbol "Cr$", so one would write Cr$13,50 for 13 cruzeiros and 50 centavos.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The *cifrão* was formerly used by the Portuguese escudo (ISO: PTE) before its replacement by the euro and by the Portuguese Timor escudo (ISO: TPE) before its replacement by the Indonesian rupiah and the US dollar.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In Portuguese and Cape Verdean usage, the *cifrão* is placed as a decimal point between the escudo and *centavo* values.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The name originates in the Arabic *ṣifr* (‏صِفْر‎), meaning 'zero'.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Outside the Portuguese cultural sphere, the South Vietnamese đồng before 1975 used a method similar to the *cifrão* to separate values of đồng from its decimal subunit *xu*.
[src:page/dollar-sign] For example, 7(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 7 đồng and 50 xu.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In some places and at some times, the one- and two-stroke variants have been used in the same contexts to distinguish between the U.S. dollar and other local currency, such as the former Portuguese escudo.
[src:page/dollar-sign] However, such usage is not standardized, and the Unicode specification considers the two versions as graphic variants of the same symbol—a typeface design choice.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Computer and typewriter keyboards usually have a single key for that sign, and many character encodings (including ASCII and Unicode) reserve a single numeric code for it.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Indeed, dollar signs in the same digital document may be rendered with one or two strokes, if different computer fonts are used, but the underlying codepoint U+0024 (ASCII 3610) remains unchanged.
[src:page/dollar-sign] When a specific variant is not mandated by law or custom, the choice is usually a matter of expediency or aesthetic preference.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Both versions were used in the US in the 18th century.
[src:page/dollar-sign] (An 1861 Civil War-era advertisement depicts the two-stroked symbol as a snake.) The two-stroke version seems to be generally less popular today, though used in some "old-style" fonts like Baskerville.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Because of its use in early American computer applications such as business accounting, the dollar sign is almost universally present in computer character sets, and thus has been appropriated for many purposes unrelated to money in programming languages and command languages.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The dollar sign "$" has ASCII and Unicode code point U+0024 (in Unicode's Latin-1 block inherited from ASCII).
[src:page/dollar-sign] There are no separate encodings for one- and two-line variants.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The choice is typeface-dependent; they are allographs.
[src:page/dollar-sign] However, there are three other code points that originate from other East Asian standards: the Taiwanese small form variant, the CJK fullwidth form, and the Japanese emoji.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The glyphs for these code points are typically larger or smaller than the primary code point, but the difference is mostly aesthetic or typographic, and the meanings of the symbols are the same.
[src:page/dollar-sign] However, for usage as the special character in various computing applications (see following sections), U+0024 is typically the only code that is recognized.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Support for the two-line variant varies.
[src:page/dollar-sign] As of 2019, the Unicode standard considers the distinction between one- and two-bar dollar signs a stylistic distinction between fonts, and has no separate code point for the *cifrão*.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The symbol is not in the October 2019 "pipeline", though it has been requested formally.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In LaTeX, with the textcomp package installed, the *cifrão* ((Dollar sign with two vertical lines)) can be input using the command `\textdollaroldstyle`.
[src:page/dollar-sign] However, because of font substitution and the lack of a dedicated code point, the author of an electronic document who uses one of these fonts intending to represent a *cifrão* cannot be sure that every reader will see a double-bar glyph rather than the single barred version.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Because of the continued lack of support in Unicode, a single bar dollar sign is frequently employed in its place even for official purposes.
[src:page/dollar-sign] Where there is any risk of misunderstanding, the ISO 4217 three-letter acronym is used.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The character U+3326 ㌦ SQUARE DORU is a squared word version of ドル (*doru* "dollar", in Japanese).
[src:page/dollar-sign] The character U+5F17 弗 CJK UNIFIED IDEOGRAPH-5F17 has been formerly repurposed as a symbol for dollars in Japan because of its visual similarity.
[src:page/dollar-sign] The symbol is sometimes used derisively, in place of the letter S, to indicate greed or excess money such as in "Micro$oft", "Di$ney", "Chel$ea" and "GW$"; or supposed overt Americanization as in "$ky".
[src:page/dollar-sign] The dollar sign is also used intentionally to stylize names such as A$AP Rocky, Ke$ha, and Ty Dolla $ign or words such as ¥€$.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In 1872, Ambrose Bierce referred to California governor Leland Stanford as $tealand Landford.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In Scrabble notation, a dollar sign is placed after a word to indicate that it is valid according to the North American word lists, but not according to the British word lists.
[src:page/dollar-sign] A dollar symbol is used as unit of reactivity for a nuclear reactor, 0 $ being the threshold of slow criticality, meaning a steady reaction rate, while 1 $ is the threshold of prompt criticality, which means a nuclear excursion or explosion.
[src:page/dollar-sign] In the 1993 version of the Turkmen Latin alphabet $ was used as a transliteration of the Cyrillic letter Ш, in 1999 was replaced by the letter Ş.
[src:page/symbol] A **symbol** is a mark, sign, or word that indicates, signifies, or is understood as representing an idea, object, relationship, or mathematical formula.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols allow people to go beyond what is known or seen by creating linkages between otherwise different concepts and experiences.
[src:page/symbol] All communication is achieved through the use of symbols: for example, a red octagon is a common symbol for "STOP"; on maps, blue lines often represent rivers; and a red rose often symbolizes love and compassion.
[src:page/symbol] Numerals are symbols for numbers; letters of an alphabet may be symbols for certain phonemes; and personal names are symbols representing individuals.
[src:page/symbol] The academic study of symbols is called semiotics.
[src:page/symbol] In the arts, symbolism is the use of a concrete element to represent a more abstract idea.
[src:page/symbol] In cartography, an organized collection of symbols forms a legend for a map.
[src:page/symbol] A literary or artistic symbol as an "outward sign" of something else is a metaphorical extension of this notion of a message from a sender to a recipient.
[src:page/symbol] In English, the meaning "something which stands for something else" was first recorded in 1590, in Edmund Spenser's *Faerie Queene*.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols are a means of complex communication that often can have multiple levels of meaning.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols are the basis of all human understanding and serve as vehicles of conception for all human knowledge.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols facilitate understanding of the world in which we live, thus serving as the grounds upon which we make judgments.
[src:page/symbol] In this way, people use symbols not only to make sense of the world around them but also to identify and cooperate in society through constitutive rhetoric.
[src:page/symbol] Human cultures use symbols to express specific ideologies and social structures and to represent aspects of their specific culture.
[src:page/symbol] Thus, symbols carry meanings that depend upon one's cultural background.
[src:page/symbol] As a result, the meaning of a symbol is not inherent in the symbol itself but is culturally learned.
[src:page/symbol] Heinrich Zimmer gives a concise overview of the nature, and perennial relevance, of symbols.
[src:page/symbol] Semiotics is the study of signs, symbols, and signification as communicative behavior.
[src:page/symbol] Semiotics studies focus on the relationship of the signifier and the signified, also taking into account the interpretation of visual cues, body language, sound, and other contextual clues.
[src:page/symbol] Semiotics is linked with linguistics and psychology.
[src:page/symbol] Semioticians not only study what a symbol implies but also how it got its meaning and how it functions to make meaning in society.
[src:page/symbol] For example, symbols can cause confusion in translation when the same symbol means different things in the source and target languages.
[src:page/symbol] A potential error documented in survey translation is the symbol of "x" used to denote "yes" when marking a response in the English language surveys, but "x" usually means "no" in the Chinese convention.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols allow the human brain continuously to create meaning using sensory input and decode symbols through both denotation and connotation.
[src:page/symbol] An alternative definition of *symbol*, distinguishing it from the term *sign* was proposed by Swiss psychoanalyst Carl Jung.
[src:page/symbol] In his studies on what is now called Jungian archetypes, a sign stands for something known, as a word stands for its referent.
[src:page/symbol] He contrasted a sign with a *symbol*: something that is unknown and that cannot be made clear or precise.
[src:page/symbol] An example of a symbol in this sense is Christ as a symbol of the archetype called *self*.
[src:page/symbol] Kenneth Burke described *Homo sapiens* as a "symbol-using, symbol making, and symbol misusing animal" to suggest that a person creates symbols as well as misuses them.
[src:page/symbol] One example he uses to indicate what he means by the misuse of the symbol is the story of a man who, when told that a particular food item was whale blubber, could barely keep from throwing it up.
[src:page/symbol] Later, his friend discovered it was actually just a dumpling.
[src:page/symbol] But the man's reaction was a direct consequence of the symbol of "blubber" representing something inedible in his mind.
[src:page/symbol] In addition, the symbol of "blubber" was created by the man through various kinds of learning.
[src:page/symbol] Burke goes on to describe symbols as also being derived from Sigmund Freud's work on condensation and displacement, further stating that symbols are not just relevant to the theory of dreams but also to "normal symbol systems".
[src:page/symbol] He says they are related through "substitution", where one word, phrase, or symbol is substituted for another in order to change the meaning.
[src:page/symbol] In other words, if one person does not understand a certain word or phrase, another person may substitute a synonym or symbol in order to get the meaning across.
[src:page/symbol] However, upon learning the new way of interpreting a specific symbol, the person may change his or her already-formed ideas to incorporate the new information.
[src:page/symbol] Jean Dalby Clift says that people not only add their own interpretations to symbols, but they also create personal symbols that represent their own understanding of their lives: what she calls "core images" of the person.
[src:page/symbol] Clift argues that symbolic work with these personal symbols or core images can be as useful as working with dream symbols in psychoanalysis or counseling.
[src:page/symbol] William Indick suggests that the symbols that are commonly found in myth, legend, and fantasy fulfill psychological functions and hence are why archetypes such as "the hero", "the princess" and "the witch" have remained popular for centuries.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols can carry symbolic value in three primary forms: Ideological, comparative, and isomorphic.
[src:page/symbol] Ideological symbols such as religious and state symbols convey complex sets of beliefs and ideas that indicate "the right thing to do".
[src:page/symbol] Comparative symbols such as prestigious office addresses, fine art, and prominent awards indicate answers to questions of "better or worse" and "superior or inferior".
[src:page/symbol] Isomorphic symbols blend in with the surrounding cultural environment such that they enable individuals and organizations to conform to their surroundings and evade social and political scrutiny.
[src:page/symbol] Examples of symbols with isomorphic value include wearing a professional dress during business meetings, shaking hands to greet others in the West, or bowing to greet others in the East.
[src:page/symbol] A single symbol can carry multiple distinct meanings such that it provides multiple types of symbolic value.
[src:page/symbol] Paul Tillich argued that, while signs are invented and forgotten, symbols are born and die.
[src:page/symbol] There are, therefore, dead and living symbols.
[src:page/symbol] A living symbol can reveal to an individual hidden levels of meaning and transcendent or religious realities.
[src:page/symbol] For Tillich a symbol always "points beyond itself" to something that is unquantifiable and mysterious; symbols open up the "depth dimension of reality itself".
[src:page/symbol] Symbols are complex, and their meanings can evolve as the individual or culture evolves.
[src:page/symbol] When a symbol loses its meaning and power for an individual or culture, it becomes a dead symbol.
[src:page/symbol] When a symbol becomes identified with the deeper reality to which it refers, it becomes idolatrous as the "symbol is taken for reality." The symbol itself is substituted for the deeper meaning it intends to convey.
[src:page/symbol] The unique nature of a symbol is that it gives access to deeper layers of reality that are otherwise inaccessible.
[src:page/symbol] A symbol's meaning may be modified by various factors including popular usage, history, and contextual intent.
[src:page/symbol] The history of a symbol is one of many factors in determining a particular symbol's apparent meaning.
[src:page/symbol] Consequently, symbols with emotive power carry problems analogous to false etymologies.
[src:page/symbol] The context of a symbol may change its meaning.
[src:page/symbol] Similar five-pointed stars might signify a law enforcement officer or a member of the armed services, depending upon the uniform.
[src:page/symbol] Symbols are used in cartography to communicate geographical information (generally as point, line, or area features).
[src:page/symbol] As with other symbols, visual variables such as size, shape, orientation, texture, and pattern provide meaning to the symbol.
[src:page/symbol] According to semiotics, map symbols are "read" by map users when they make a connection between the graphic mark on the map (the *sign*), a general concept (the *interpretant*), and a particular feature of the real world (the *referent*).
[src:page/symbol] A **symbolic action** is an action that symbolizes or signals what the actor wants or believes.
[src:page/symbol] The action conveys meaning to the viewers.
[src:page/symbol] Symbolic action may overlap with symbolic speech, such as the use of flag burning to express hostility or saluting the flag to express patriotism.
[src:page/symbol] In response to intense public criticism, businesses, organizations, and governments may take symbolic actions rather than, or in addition to, directly addressing the identified problems.
[src:page/symbol] Unicode (also known as *The Unicode Standard* and TUS) is a character encoding standard maintained by the Unicode Consortium designed to support the use of text in all of the world's writing systems that can be digitized.
[src:page/symbol] Version 17.0 defines 159,801 characters and 172 scripts used in various ordinary, literary, academic and technical contexts.
[src:page/symbol] Unicode has largely supplanted the previous environment of myriad incompatible character sets used within different locales and on different computer architectures.
[src:page/symbol] The entire repertoire of these sets, plus many additional characters, were merged into the single Unicode set.
[src:page/symbol] Unicode is used to encode the vast majority of text on the Internet, including most web pages, and relevant Unicode support has become a common consideration in contemporary software development.
[src:page/symbol] Unicode is ultimately capable of encoding more than 1.1 million characters.
[src:page/symbol] The Unicode character repertoire is synchronized with ISO/IEC 10646, each being code-for-code identical with one another.
[src:page/symbol] However, *The Unicode Standard* is more than just a repertoire within which characters are assigned.
[src:page/symbol] To aid developers and designers, the standard also provides charts and reference data, as well as annexes explaining concepts germane to various scripts, providing guidance for their implementation.
[src:page/symbol] Topics covered by these annexes include character normalization, character composition and decomposition, collation, and directionality.
[src:page/symbol] Unicode encodes 3,790 emoji, with the continued development thereof conducted by the Consortium as a part of the standard.
[src:page/symbol] The widespread adoption of Unicode was in large part responsible for the initial popularization of emoji outside of Japan.
[src:page/symbol] Unicode text is processed and stored as binary data using one of several encodings, which define how to translate the standard's abstracted codes for characters into sequences of bytes.
[src:page/symbol] *The Unicode Standard* itself defines three encodings: UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, though several others exist.
[src:page/symbol] UTF-8 is the most widely used by a large margin, in part due to its backwards-compatibility with ASCII.
